               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of Ḥabīb al-siyar fī akhbār afrād al-bashar by Khvāndamīr</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85148201 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85067895" n="1" xml:id="Uk_Delhi_Persian_629B-item1">
                     <textLang mainLang="fa" otherLangs="ar">Persian and Arabic</textLang>
                     <note>
                        <p>Substantial fragment from an early section of the universal history, entitled 
                <title key="work_645">Ḥabīb al-siyar fī akhbār afrād al-bashar</title>, by the Timurid (Mughal) and later Safavid polymath historian 
                <persName key="ark:/81055/vdc_100164657805.0x000001 viaf_45109504" role="aut">Mīr Ghiyās̲ al-Dīn ibn Humām al-Dīn al-Ḥusaynī</persName>, known as Khvāndamīr (d. 942/1536), written under the patronage of and dedicated to the Safavid governor of Herat, 
                <persName key="person_f8138" role="pat dte">Mīrzā Karīm al-Dīn Ḥabīb Allāh Sāvajī</persName>, who ordered the updating and correcting of the universal history, the 
                <title key="work_645">Rawz̤at al-ṣafāʾ fī sīrat al-anbiyāʾ va al-mulūk va al-khulafāʾ</title>, composed earlier under patronage of the Timurid noble, 
                <persName key="viaf_22198747" role="oth">Amīr ʿAlī Shīr Navāʾī</persName>(d. 906/1501), by the historian’s maternal grandfather, 
                <persName key="viaf_175393012" role="oth">Mīr Muḥammad ibn Burhān al-Dīn Khāvand Shāh ibn Maḥmūd al-Ḥusaynī al-Bukhārī</persName>, known as Mīr Khvānd (d. 903/1498).
                        </p>
                        <p>This copy comprises part of the opening introduction or iftitāḥ and the first section termed majlad, covering accounts of the early prophets down to the early caliphs.</p>
                        <p>Defective at the beginning and end.</p>
                        <p>Lacunae in the original text are replaced by later leaves transcribed in an awkward nastaʿlīq hand.</p>
                        <p>Original text in scribal naskh, occasional rubrication, other headings supplied by a later hand in margins.</p>
                        <p>Not dated at end; datable to the late sixteenth century with replacement leaves dating to the early eighteenth century.</p>
                        <p>Annotations in margins.</p>
                        <p>Not foliated.</p>
                        <p>Original covers lost.</p>
                        <p>Damaged binding of painted and tooled reddish leather edged with brown leather; detached spine, paste boards delaminating (revealing Arabic text, from copies the 
                <title key="work_645">Qurʾān</title>, ḥadīs̲, and grammatical texts).
                        </p>
                        <p>Folios mostly unbound; water and fungal stains, cropped, creased, later repairs.</p>
                     </note>
